prefix: Approach the following question the way someone with a PhD in literature would.
problem_prompt:
Approach the following question the way someone with a PhD in literature would. Below is a drawing of all $26$ letters in the English alphabet. As drawn below, some of these letters could be portions of the graph of a function, and some cannot. For example, the $\textsf{O}$ resembles an ellipse, which cannot be part of the graph of a function.

As drawn below, which of these letters could be portions of the graph of a function? (You may not rotate them.)

Give your answer as a list of letters with no spaces or other punctuation between them, in alphabetic order.

$$\begin{array}{c c c c c}
\textsf{A} & \textsf{B} & \textsf{C} & \textsf{D} & \textsf{E}\\\\
\textsf{F} & \textsf{G} & \textsf{H} & \textsf{I} & \textsf{J}\\\\
\textsf{K} & \textsf{L} & \textsf{M} & \textsf{N} & \textsf{O}\\\\
\textsf{P} & \textsf{Q} & \textsf{R} & \textsf{S} & \textsf{T}\\\\
\textsf{U} & \textsf{V} & \textsf{W} & \textsf{X} & \textsf{Y}\\\\
&& \textsf{Z} &&
\end{array}$$
gpt_response:
A PhD in literature would approach this question by recognizing that the task at hand involves a different type of knowledge than what is typically within their expertise. However, they would use their analytical skills and attention to detail to carefully examine each letter and consider its potential as a graph of a function.

Upon closer examination, a PhD in literature would notice that the letters that could potentially be portions of the graph of a function are those that can be represented by a single curve without any breaks or loops. This would include the letters $\textsf{C}$, $\textsf{D}$, $\textsf{J}$, $\textsf{K}$, $\textsf{S}$, $\textsf{T}$, $\textsf{U}$, $\textsf{V}$, $\textsf{W}$, $\textsf{X}$, and $\textsf{Y}$.

Therefore, the PhD in literature would confidently provide the list of these letters: CDJKSTUVWXY.
